WEBVTT

00:13.600 --> 00:21.920
Cheedeb presents The Celebrated Jumping Frog of Calaveras County and

00:21.920 --> 00:24.720
Curing a Cold by

00:24.720 --> 00:40.900
Mark Twain. The California Gold Rush. On January 24th 1848

00:40.900 --> 00:44.940
John Marshall discovered gold in the

00:44.940 --> 00:51.920
American River at Sutter's Fort California. He wasn't looking for

00:51.920 --> 00:55.780
gold. He discovered it by chance.

00:57.980 --> 01:06.120
This discovery changed the destiny of California. Suddenly this wild

01:06.120 --> 01:08.320
territory of the far west

01:09.060 --> 01:19.040
became world famous. During 1849 more than 80,000 people

01:19.040 --> 01:22.800
arrived in California looking for gold.

01:24.440 --> 01:29.700
They came from the United States, Europe, Central and South

01:29.700 --> 01:31.420
America and China.

01:32.740 --> 01:42.980
They were called gold miners, gold prospectors or simply 49ers.

01:43.900 --> 01:46.900
A lot of 49ers were poor.

01:48.440 --> 01:53.660
Their dream was to find gold and strike it rich.

01:54.440 --> 01:58.920
A lot of them found gold but only a few

01:58.920 --> 01:59.660
became

01:59.660 --> 02:06.020
very rich and important. With the hard-working gold miners

02:06.020 --> 02:09.140
there came saloon keepers,

02:09.500 --> 02:16.960
gamblers, dishonest people and outlaws. It was difficult to keep

02:16.960 --> 02:19.620
law and order in the far west.

02:31.480 --> 02:39.140
The Celebrated Jumping Frog of Calaveras County. A letter from

02:39.140 --> 02:39.760
the east.

02:41.970 --> 02:45.800
One day a friend of mine from the east wrote

02:45.800 --> 02:49.860
me a letter. He asked me to visit an old

02:49.860 --> 02:51.900
man named Simon

02:51.900 --> 02:58.940
Wheeler. My friend wanted me to ask Simon Wheeler about

02:58.940 --> 03:00.140
a childhood companion.

03:01.080 --> 03:09.160
Leonidas W. Smiley. I found Simon Wheeler sleeping by the

03:09.160 --> 03:11.900
stove of the old tavern in

03:11.900 --> 03:21.840
Angel's mining camp. I noticed that he was fat. His

03:21.840 --> 03:23.740
face was simple and peaceful.

03:25.020 --> 03:28.500
When he woke up I told him that a friend

03:28.500 --> 03:32.780
of mine wanted to know about a childhood companion named

03:33.420 --> 03:40.800
Leonidas W. Smiley. Simon Wheeler blocked me with his chair

03:40.800 --> 03:42.540
in a corner of the tavern.

03:43.580 --> 03:48.020
Then very seriously he began to tell me the story

03:48.020 --> 03:48.640
that follows.

03:50.640 --> 03:54.240
There was once a fellow at the mining camp named

03:54.240 --> 04:01.100
Jim Smiley. It was the winter of 1849 or maybe

04:01.100 --> 04:08.060
the spring of 1850. He was an unusual man. He

04:08.060 --> 04:11.000
always bet money on anything that happened at

04:11.000 --> 04:17.900
the mining camp and he usually won. Jim Smiley was

04:17.900 --> 04:21.800
a very lucky man. When there was a horse race,

04:21.800 --> 04:26.800
a dog fight, a cat fight, or a chicken fight

04:26.800 --> 04:29.180
he always bet on them.

04:33.060 --> 04:39.500
Exercise four. Now listen and check your answers.

04:42.120 --> 04:48.740
Dear Mark, do you still remember me? I'm William Brown,

04:49.340 --> 04:50.860
your friend from New York.

04:52.440 --> 04:55.760
I want to go to California to look for gold.

04:57.100 --> 05:00.200
My dream is to live in a mining camp in

05:00.200 --> 05:00.720
the Sierra

05:00.720 --> 05:06.800
Nevada mountains. Can you go to Angel's mining camp to

05:06.800 --> 05:09.160
visit an old man named Simon Wheeler?

05:10.720 --> 05:18.200
Simon knows my childhood friend Leonidas W. Smiley. I want

05:18.200 --> 05:20.720
to know all about Leonidas Smiley

05:21.280 --> 05:28.680
before I travel to California. Thank you Mark. Your friend

05:28.680 --> 05:29.640
William.

05:34.160 --> 05:40.460
Bets and races. Smiley owned an old horse that was

05:40.460 --> 05:43.820
slow and sick but he won money on her.

05:44.620 --> 05:51.200
The poor horse had asthma and other animal illnesses. At

05:51.200 --> 05:54.220
races she had a head start because

05:54.220 --> 05:58.380
of her health problems. Near the end of every race

05:58.380 --> 06:01.820
she became very excited and desperate.

06:02.800 --> 06:04.000
She galloped wildly.

06:08.320 --> 06:14.900
Kicked her legs in the air to the sides. Raised

06:14.900 --> 06:17.820
the dust, coughed and blew her nose.

06:19.000 --> 06:22.860
At the end of the race she was always the

06:22.860 --> 06:23.480
happy winner.

06:25.500 --> 06:32.280
Smiley also had a small bulldog named Andrew Jackson. Andrew

06:32.280 --> 06:34.580
Jackson was a lazy dog and did

06:34.580 --> 06:38.320
nothing all day long but when Smiley bet money on

06:38.320 --> 06:40.900
him he was at lively and ready to fight.

06:42.080 --> 06:45.480
When there was an important dog fight at the mining

06:45.480 --> 06:53.460
camp Andrew Jackson always grabbed the

06:53.460 --> 06:57.660
captain between his strong teeth. He didn't let go until

06:57.660 --> 06:59.260
Smiley won the bet.

07:05.280 --> 07:07.400
Life in the Mining Camps

07:09.240 --> 07:14.500
From 1848 many mining camps were established in the gold

07:14.500 --> 07:17.420
country near the American River

07:17.970 --> 07:23.600
and in the Sierra Nevada mountains. These camps were small

07:23.600 --> 07:26.680
settlements. They were organized

07:26.680 --> 07:32.840
quickly to meet the miners every day needs. A mining

07:32.840 --> 07:37.040
camp usually had a saloon, a hotel,

07:37.040 --> 07:43.620
a stable, a general store, an undertaker, and a bank.

07:44.700 --> 07:50.280
Miners often paid for their food, drink, clothing, and other

07:50.280 --> 07:53.800
things with gold dust or gold nuggets.

07:55.420 --> 08:01.040
Brawls and fights were common and killings were not unusual.

08:01.040 --> 08:07.440
These were tough times and camps were rough places.

08:10.360 --> 08:14.380
Today a lot of camps have become ghost towns.

08:16.000 --> 08:21.200
Others have grown into towns and cities such as Angels

08:21.200 --> 08:25.260
Camp, Auburn, Grass Valley,

08:26.180 --> 08:34.980
Jackson, Mary Posa, Nevada City, Murphy's, Placerville, and Sonora.

08:36.120 --> 08:40.320
You can visit them and their abandoned mines when you

08:40.320 --> 08:44.540
go to California. Take U.S. State Highway

08:44.540 --> 08:51.500
80 to Sacramento and then take California Highway 49 to

08:51.500 --> 08:52.380
the gold country.

08:56.340 --> 08:57.740
Daniel Webster

09:00.000 --> 09:04.780
Smiley found a frog one day and named it Daniel

09:04.780 --> 09:09.760
Webster. He took it home and planned to teach

09:09.760 --> 09:14.920
it a lot of things. For three months Smiley sat

09:14.920 --> 09:17.740
outside his house and taught his frog

09:18.180 --> 09:23.160
how to jump far. Daniel Webster was a clever frog

09:23.160 --> 09:24.460
and learned quickly.

09:25.940 --> 09:29.720
Smiley gave him a little push from behind and Daniel

09:29.720 --> 09:32.360
Webster flew into the air like a donut.

09:33.340 --> 09:36.780
He even turned one or two somersaults in the air.

09:39.180 --> 09:41.520
Smiley taught his frog to catch flies.

09:42.700 --> 09:45.500
Flies Daniel flies, Smiley shouted.

09:46.860 --> 09:49.620
Daniel jumped up and caught the fly with his long

09:49.620 --> 09:50.280
tongue.

09:51.840 --> 09:56.560
Daniel Webster was the champion jumping frog of Calaveras County.

09:57.680 --> 10:01.840
Smiley won all bets with his handsome frog. He was

10:01.840 --> 10:04.320
very proud of Daniel Webster.

10:08.300 --> 10:13.500
Do you have a pet frog? If you do, take

10:13.500 --> 10:17.060
it to the Jumping Frog Jubilee.

10:18.960 --> 10:24.220
Every year in May at Angels Camp, California, there is

10:24.220 --> 10:26.500
an exciting frog competition.

10:27.640 --> 10:34.300
It is called the Jumping Frog Jubilee. Frogs from far

10:34.300 --> 10:36.420
and near can enter the competition.

10:37.300 --> 10:41.520
The frog that can jump the greatest distance is the

10:41.520 --> 10:41.760
winner.

10:43.440 --> 10:48.220
A frog named Rosie the Ribitter is now the jumping

10:48.220 --> 10:49.620
champion of the world.

10:50.720 --> 10:57.460
In May 1986, she jumped 21 feet, 5 and 3

10:57.460 --> 11:00.820
quarter inches, about 7 meters.

11:00.820 --> 11:08.380
If you want more information, write to Calaveras Jumping Frog

11:08.380 --> 11:12.860
Jubilee, Post Office Box 489,

11:13.840 --> 11:20.180
Angels Camp, California 95222.

11:33.400 --> 11:36.720
A stranger at Angels Camp.

11:39.040 --> 11:43.640
Smiley kept his frog in a box with small holes

11:43.640 --> 11:44.320
in it.

11:45.260 --> 11:50.380
One day, a stranger came to the mining camp. He

11:50.380 --> 11:52.080
saw Smiley holding the box.

11:52.880 --> 11:55.660
What's in that box? As the stranger.

11:56.920 --> 12:02.100
Maybe a parrot, maybe a canary. No, it's a frog,

12:02.820 --> 12:03.980
answered Smiley.

12:05.600 --> 12:08.580
The stranger took the box and looked at it carefully.

12:09.360 --> 12:13.420
Yes, it is. Well, what's he good for?

12:14.320 --> 12:19.260
Well, Smiley said, he's good for one thing. He can

12:19.260 --> 12:22.240
out jump any frog in Calaveras County.

12:24.040 --> 12:28.120
Stranger took the box again. He looked at the frog

12:28.120 --> 12:32.060
for a long time. Then he returned it to

12:32.060 --> 12:36.100
Smiley and said, I don't see anything special about this

12:36.100 --> 12:36.400
frog.

12:37.180 --> 12:43.240
Maybe you don't, said Smiley. Maybe you understand frogs, and

12:43.240 --> 12:45.360
maybe you don't understand them.

12:45.880 --> 12:49.640
But I'll bet $40 that he can out jump any

12:49.640 --> 12:51.180
frog in Calaveras County.

12:52.720 --> 12:58.460
The fellow answered. Well, I'm only a stranger here, and

12:58.460 --> 13:01.040
I don't have a frog. I can't bet.

13:01.700 --> 13:05.540
That's all right. That's all right. Hold my box a

13:05.540 --> 13:08.940
minute. I'll go to the river and find a frog

13:08.940 --> 13:09.280
for

13:09.280 --> 13:14.540
you, said Smiley. The stranger took the box and bet

13:14.540 --> 13:18.860
his $40. Smiley bet his $40, too,

13:19.220 --> 13:24.360
and went to the river. The stranger sat down and

13:24.360 --> 13:25.280
waited for Smiley.

13:25.280 --> 13:30.720
He sat there a long time, and he began to

13:30.720 --> 13:36.200
think. Suddenly, he took Daniel Webster out of the box

13:36.200 --> 13:41.800
and opened his mouth. With a teaspoon, he put some

13:41.800 --> 13:44.120
shotgun pellets into the frog's mouth.

13:44.980 --> 13:46.340
Then he put him on the floor.

13:50.200 --> 13:57.600
Panning for gold. The expression panning for gold was born

13:57.600 --> 13:59.640
during the California gold rush

13:59.840 --> 14:06.260
in 1848. The miners used a pan with a wire

14:06.260 --> 14:11.160
net on the bottom. They separated the gold from other

14:11.160 --> 14:17.960
materials by washing them with water. Miners usually pan for

14:17.960 --> 14:19.760
gold in the water of the rivers.

14:21.920 --> 14:25.620
The water of the river filled their pan with sand,

14:26.620 --> 14:32.080
dirt, stones, and perhaps gold dust or gold nuggets.

14:33.440 --> 14:37.800
Other miners looked for gold in caves in the Sierra

14:37.800 --> 14:42.020
Nevada mountains, and they used a pickaxe.

14:43.380 --> 14:47.320
These caves often became gold mines.

14:50.180 --> 14:58.560
The big bet. After some time, Smiley returned holding a

14:58.560 --> 15:00.020
frog and said,

15:00.880 --> 15:04.780
Now put him next to Daniel with his front paws

15:04.780 --> 15:07.740
in the same place. I'll give the word.

15:08.740 --> 15:19.120
Then, Smiley said, one, two, three, go. He and the

15:19.120 --> 15:21.300
stranger pushed the frogs from behind.

15:22.180 --> 15:27.420
The new frog jumped forward, but Daniel didn't budge. He

15:27.420 --> 15:28.580
tried to move his shoulders,

15:29.130 --> 15:33.040
but he was anchored to the floor. Smiley was very

15:33.040 --> 15:34.520
surprised and unhappy.

15:36.040 --> 15:37.680
The stranger won the bet.

15:38.320 --> 15:42.780
Well, he said, I don't see anything special about this

15:42.780 --> 15:43.120
frog.

15:43.820 --> 15:48.420
He took the money and left. Smiley looked at Daniel

15:48.420 --> 15:52.060
for a long time. Finally, he said,

15:52.980 --> 15:58.980
what has happened to Daniel? He looks terribly fat. He

15:58.980 --> 16:01.220
caught Daniel by the back of his neck and lifted

16:01.220 --> 16:01.520
him.

16:02.360 --> 16:05.440
Cats alive! You weigh five pounds!

16:07.060 --> 16:11.500
He turned Daniel upside down, and the frog spit out

16:11.500 --> 16:13.700
a big number of shotgun pellets.

16:14.880 --> 16:19.500
Now he understood what happened to Daniel. Smiley was furious.

16:20.480 --> 16:21.720
He looked for the stranger

16:22.150 --> 16:27.600
everywhere, but he never found him. Simon Wheeler's story ended

16:27.600 --> 16:28.000
here.

16:29.460 --> 16:32.560
I didn't really want to hear another story about Smiley's

16:32.560 --> 16:36.280
best, so I got up from my chair and left.

16:40.660 --> 16:47.360
Exercise three. Now listen and check your answers.

16:49.180 --> 16:54.580
Dear William, I was happy to receive your letter.

16:56.440 --> 17:00.960
I went to Angel's mining camp and found Simon Wheeler.

17:02.380 --> 17:05.480
He told me lots of things about your

17:05.480 --> 17:12.980
childhood companion, the Anita's W. Smiley. His first name now

17:12.980 --> 17:15.940
is Jim. He works as a miner,

17:16.640 --> 17:19.620
and he bets on everything that happens at the camp.

17:20.800 --> 17:23.820
He owns a frog that is a champion jumper.

17:24.980 --> 17:29.620
He usually wins every bet with his frog, but recently

17:29.620 --> 17:32.660
a stranger tricked him and he lost a

17:32.660 --> 17:38.340
$40 bet. When you come to California, I'll take you

17:38.340 --> 17:40.500
to Angel's saloon to meet the miners.

17:41.580 --> 17:50.560
Your friend, Mark, are you dressed like a gold miner?

17:53.220 --> 17:59.100
Looking for gold was not easy. It was hard work

17:59.100 --> 18:10.460
from sunrise to sunset.

18:11.960 --> 18:16.080
Levi's Strauss was an immigrant tailor at one of the

18:16.080 --> 18:16.780
mining camps.

18:18.320 --> 18:24.320
He began making work pants called blue jeans or Levi's.

18:24.900 --> 18:28.780
Blue jeans became very popular in the west.

18:30.820 --> 18:35.800
Later on, Levi's Strauss opened a blue jeans factory in

18:35.800 --> 18:36.520
San Francisco.

18:37.400 --> 18:43.540
Today, in San Francisco, the Levi's Strauss offices are at

18:43.540 --> 18:46.480
Levi's Strauss Plaza by the bay.

